Q2. Implement learning with
a more biologically plausible
learning rule than
backpropagation (e.g.,
Hebbian learning, weight
perturbation, feedback
alignment, Kolen-Pollack
algorithm) and train the
same network again with the
same hyperparameters, but
using this learning rule.
Q3. Measure a few performance
metrics of the different networks,
like (1) rate of learning, (2) final
test loss, (3) robustness when
noise is added to the inputs.
Q4. Compare these
metrics for the
networks trained with
different learning
rules. Do some
learning rules perform
better than others?
What might explain
this?
Q5. Evaluate how consistent these metrics are. If you
implement a few biologically plausible learning rules, and
train several FFNs, initialized with different random seeds,
can you infer which learning rule was used based only on its
metrics? You can assess this visually by looking at whether
the metrics of the same learning rule cluster together or
quantify it by training a logistic regression to predict the
learning rules from their metrics.
Q8. So far, we have been training the same FFN with
the same hyperparameters. Now try varying the
hyperparameters (e.g., different number of hidden
units, learning rate, initialization). How does this
affect our ability to infer which learning rule a
network was trained with?

Q10. Implement more complex biologically-inspired
learning rules, for example predictive coding or ones
used in spiking networks (e.g., STDP, Burstprop). How
do they perform in more difficult learning scenarios?
Q7. Measure some learning metrics, i.e., the bias and variance of the
weight updates proposed by the biologically plausible rule you have
selected. To do this, you can calculate the update proposed for each
test set item by (1) backpropagation, and (2) your learning rule. You
can then estimate the bias by calculating the cosine similarity
between the mean updates proposed by each on the test set. You can
evaluate the variance of your learning rule by calculating the signal to
noise ratio (SNR) of the proposed test set updates. A high SNR
compared to backpropagation would correspond to low variance.
Q6. Evaluate and compare the performance of networks
trained with different learning rules in more difficult
learning scenarios, e.g. online learning (i.e., learning with a
batch size of 1), and learning from non-stationary data (e.g.,
where certain MNIST digit classes only appear in the
training set partway through learning).
Q9. Try the same analysis, but in a scenario where
the quality of the metrics you can collect is lower
(e.g., only every 5th learning step was recorded, or
weight update statistics could only be recorded in
one third of the neurons). This would likely be the
case if we were collecting this data in the brain. How
does the lower metric quality affect our ability to infer
which learning rule a network was trained with?
